WEBVTT

1
00:00.300 --> 00:03.960
- Welcome back to Understanding Quantum Information and Computation.

2
00:03.960 --> 00:09.900
My name is John Watrous and I'm the Technical Director for
Education at IBM Quantum.

3
00:09.900 --> 00:19.170
This is the seventh lesson of the series and in this lesson we'll discuss the phase estimation problem and how we can solve it
with a quantum computer.

4
00:19.170 --> 00:25.980
We'll then apply phase estimation to the problem of integer factorization, which we discussed in the previous lesson.

5
00:25.980 --> 00:34.320
What we'll obtain is Shor's algorithm, which allows integers to be
factorized at polynomial cost or in polynomial time if we prefer

6
00:34.320 --> 00:39.660
to think in terms of the time required rather than the number of
elementary operations we need.

7
00:39.660 --> 00:46.295
This is the crown jewel of
quantum algorithms in some sense, and while factorized large integers

8
00:46.295 --> 00:54.990
may have limited utility for most people, it remains one of the most
compelling pieces of evidence that we have for the hypothesis that quantum computers will
offer striking advantages

9
00:54.990 --> 00:59.910
over classical computers. Here's an overview of the lesson.

10
00:59.910 --> 01:08.520
We'll start with a definition of the phase estimation problem itself, and then we'll discuss a method for solving this problem
with a quantum computer.

11
01:08.520 --> 01:14.310
We'll take it one step at a time, beginning with what you can
think of as a kind of a warmup.

12
01:14.310 --> 01:21.480
In the phase estimation problem, the goal is to approximate
a certain real number and in this warmup part
we'll see how we can get

13
01:21.480 --> 01:25.350
a very low precision
approximation to this number.

14
01:25.350 --> 01:32.310
This isn't going to be
good enough for factoring when we apply our solution to
the phase estimation problem to integer factorization,

15
01:32.310 --> 01:38.730
we're actually going to need a pretty high precision approximation, but it's nevertheless useful to begin with this sort of a warmup

16
01:38.730 --> 01:42.510
just to get a sense for
how the whole thing works.

17
01:42.510 --> 01:51.720
We'll then discuss the issue of how we can get more precision, and this will lead very
naturally to an operation known as the Quantum Fourier transform.

18
01:51.720 --> 01:57.240
We'll see exactly what this operation is and how it can be implemented
with a quantum circuit.

19
01:57.240 --> 02:06.270
And once we have it, we'll be able to apply
it to phase estimation to come up with a general procedure for solving the problem
with very high precision.

20
02:06.270 --> 02:13.680
Then in the last part of the lesson, we'll see how a solution to
the phase estimation problem allows us to factor integers efficiently.

21
02:13.680 --> 02:22.050
And specifically what we'll get is Shor's algorithm for
integer factorization, or at least something that's equivalent to Shor's algorithm.

22
02:22.050 --> 02:30.330
The way that this works is that we basically give
ourselves a stepping stone, which is yet another problem called the order finding problem.

23
02:30.330 --> 02:38.310
And in particular we'll see how we can solve the order finding problem using the phase estimation procedure and then we'll see how
we can factor integers

24
02:38.310 --> 02:45.300
by solving the order finding problem. We're going to begin with a special case of a theorem called the Spectral theorem,

25
02:45.300 --> 02:51.810
and specifically we're going to focus on what the theorem tells
us for unitary matrices.

26
02:51.810 --> 02:57.420
The spectral theorem is
a very important theorem from linear algebra and
functional analysis.

27
02:57.420 --> 03:04.800
It tells us something interesting about how certain linear mappings can be expressed in a certain form, it's often called a
spectral decomposition,

28
03:04.800 --> 03:08.700
that's useful for many reasons.

29
03:08.700 --> 03:15.300
And like I said, we're going to focus on what this theorem tells
us for unitary matrices.

30
03:15.300 --> 03:21.960
The spectral theorem is
more general than this. It doesn't work for all matrices, but it does work for a class of matrices

31
03:21.960 --> 03:28.680
called normal matrices, which include all unitary matrices as well as some matrices
that aren't unitary.

32
03:28.680 --> 03:38.490
But just to keep things simple, we'll restrict our attention
to unitary matrices for now because that's all we need for
the purposes of this lesson.

33
03:38.490 --> 03:43.890
Here's a statement of the spectral theorem just for unitary matrices.

34
03:43.890 --> 03:48.240
Suppose that U is an
N by N unitary matrix.

35
03:48.240 --> 03:54.480
What the theorem says
is that there must exist an orthonormal basis of
vectors, psi one through psi N,

36
03:54.480 --> 04:04.590
along with N complex numbers
Lambda one through Lambda N, all lying on the complex unit circle so that U can be expressed
as we have in this equation.

37
04:04.590 --> 04:12.780
This is called a spectral
decomposition of U, as I've already mentioned, and it can be very convenient to know that U can be written in this way.

38
04:12.780 --> 04:20.670
It can sometimes be convenient to have these vectors and these numbers when we're working with
a particular unitary matrix U, and it can also be very
useful simply to know

39
04:20.670 --> 04:28.050
that such an expression is always possible as a way of proving certain things about unitary matrices for instance.

40
04:28.050 --> 04:34.080
In this statement of the theorem, each of these numbers,
Lambda one through lambda N, is written in a particular way

41
04:34.080 --> 04:42.180
as E to the power two pi I times theta where each of the thetas
theta one through theta N is a real number, and
we'll come back to this way

42
04:42.180 --> 04:45.750
of writing each of these
numbers in just a little bit.

43
04:45.750 --> 04:55.830
An important thing to notice
about these vectors and numbers is that each vector psi
K must be an eigenvector of the matrix U with
corresponding eigenvalue lambda K.

44
04:55.830 --> 05:01.920
Which means that if we
multiply psi K by U, what we get is lambda K times psi K.

45
05:01.920 --> 05:09.540
So what U does to each of these vectors is simply to multiply it by the corresponding number lambda K.

46
05:09.540 --> 05:15.540
In general for some arbitrary vector, this won't be how U works, but eigenvectors are special.

47
05:15.540 --> 05:21.240
And what the theorem tells us is that there is in fact
an ortho normal basis of these eigenvectors.

48
05:21.240 --> 05:30.420
This equation down here by the way, follows from the expression that we have for U from the theorem, together with the fact that
the vectors are orthonormal.

